## 6. Training Trajectory (Loss Curve Analysis)

The following chart outlines the Validation SI-SDR performance (higher is better) mapped across epochs, extracted directly from the tmux training logs.

| Epoch | Baseline Model (v1) | Scaled Model (v2) | Status / Notes |
| :--- | :--- | :--- | :--- |
| **10** | *(History truncated)* | `0.68 dB` | Scaled model starts completely collapsed |
| **20** | *(History truncated)* | `0.68 dB` | Flatlining... |
| **30** | *(History truncated)* | `0.71 dB` | Flatlining... |
| **40** | *(History truncated)* | `0.65 dB` | Flatlining... |
| **50** | *(History truncated)* | `0.70 dB` | Flatlining... |
| **60** | *(History truncated)* | `0.75 dB` | Flatlining... |
| **70** | *(History truncated)* | `0.75 dB` | Flatlining... |
| **80** | `10.43 dB` | `0.72 dB` | Baseline model separating audio flawlessly |
| **90** | `10.62 dB` | `0.77 dB` | Baseline fully converges |
| **100** | **`10.63 dB`** | **`0.81 dB`** | **Training complete.** |

### Diagnostic Conclusion
The massively scaled `v2` architecture completely failed to converge. 
1. **Vanishing Gradients**: Deepening the network from 8 to 10 blocks per repeat dramatically altered the gradient flow across 4 temporal repeats. A training learning rate of `1e-3` (which worked for the smaller baseline) was far too aggressive for an un-regularized network of this size, immediately pushing the weights into a collapsed local minimum early in training (as seen by the flatline at ~0.7 dB).
2. **Data-Starvation**: Scaling to `B=256` and `H=1024` effectively squares the parameter limit. Feeding this giant model just `1000` isolated batch steps per epoch of clean LibriSpeech without intense audio augmentations (like MUSAN background noise or speed perturbation) inherently forces parameter collapse.

**Final Recommendation:** To actually take advantage of the massive scaled H200 model, you must lower the Learning Rate to `1e-4` and massively increase the batch size and noise augmentations!
